data.title: Polestar (Nasdaq: PSNY) receives Nasdaq notice for not meeting $1.00 minimum bid price requirement, has until 29 April 2026 to regain compliance.
data.description: Polestar, a Swedish company trading on Nasdaq under the symbol PSNY, recently received a notice from the Nasdaq Stock Market LLC stating that it does not currently meet the minimum bid price requirement of $1.00 per share as per Nasdaq Listing Rule 5450(a)(1). The company has been given 180 days, until April 29, 2026, to raise its closing bid price to $1.00 or above per ADS (American Depositary Share) for at least 10 consecutive business days to regain compliance, in accordance with Nasdaq Listing Rule 5810(c)(3)(A).

data.title: Navan, Inc. closes IPO, selling 36.9M shares at $25 each for total of $923.1M, with 30M from company and 6.9M from stockholders.
data.description: Navan, Inc., a company based in Palo Alto, California, specializing in business travel, payments, and expense management, recently completed its initial public offering on the NASDAQ under the ticker symbol NAVN. The IPO involved the sale of a total of 36,924,406 shares of Class A common stock at a price of $25.00 per share. Of these shares, 30,000,000 were offered by Navan, while the remaining 6,924,406 shares were sold by existing stockholders known as the "Selling Stockholders."

data.title: Mary Laschinger joins Stanley Black & Decker Board of Directors on Nov. 1, 2025. Former Veritiv CEO. NYSE: SWK.
data.description: In New Britain, Connecticut on October 31, 2025, Stanley Black & Decker (NYSE: SWK) revealed the appointment of Mary Laschinger, the former Chair and CEO of Veritiv Corporation, to its Board of Directors. This decision will be effective starting November 1, 2025. Mary Laschinger brings a wealth of experience from her tenure at Veritiv Corporation and has been an influential figure in the industry for many years. This new addition highlights Stanley Black & Decker's commitment to diversifying its board and tapping into the expertise of accomplished leaders.

data.title: Dexcom stock falls 15% due to cautious outlook despite solid Q3 report. Investors concerned.
data.description: The third-quarter report from Dexcom, a leading company in the medical technology sector, was generally positive. However, the company's stock faced a significant setback on Friday as it plummeted by 15%. This drop was primarily attributed to Dexcom's outlook for the future, which was perceived as overly cautious by investors and analysts. Despite posting solid financial results for the quarter, the company's stock performance was overshadowed by concerns raised due to the conservative outlook. This development was highlighted in a recent article published by Investor's Business Daily.

data.title: Wesco International stock earns 87 RS Rating, showing strong performance.
data.description: Wesco International's Relative Strength Rating has surged to over 80. The company's stock has earned an impressive rating of 87 RS. This development indicates a strong performance compared to other stocks in the market.
